> On November 6, 2012 9:16:23 PM boswell alan <alan.boswell@blueyonder.co.uk>
> wrote:
>>
>> Hi Zilvinas
>> It's a difficult question that depends on how much efficiency you are
>> looking for.  A quarterwave vertical seems to need about 12 lambda/4
>> radials for 75% radiation efficiency.  For a halfwave my guess would
>> be six - but 12 would always be better :)
>> Alan G3NOQ
>>
>>
>>
>> On 6 November 2012 12:54, Zilvinas, AUGMA <zilvinas@augma.lt> wrote:
>> >
>> > On 2012.11.06 13:47, boswell alan wrote:
>> >>
>> >> Quarterwave and halfwave verticals are both resonant, but the halfwave
>> >> has a higher impedance with less base-current, so in principle the
>> >> ground losses can be covered adequately with less wire in the ground
>> >> plane.
>> >
>> > Does anybody know how much wire I need for radials in this case?
>> >
>> >>   A slightly larger 5/8-lambda vertical maximises the gain along
>> >> the ground, and although there is some reactance in the base-impedance
>> >> that is not usually a big problem.
>> >
>> > The same question - how much wire for 5/8 then is sufficient?
>> >
>> > Thanks!
>> >
>> > 73 Zilvis LY2SS
